==Utica in popular culture and literature== * Utica is mentioned in [[Allen Ginsberg]]'s poem [[Howl]] (''"I'm with you in Rockland / where you drink the tea of the / breasts of the spinsters of Utica"'' ).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pangloss.com/seidel/Ramble/howl_text.html |title=HOWL |author=Allen Ginsberg |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> * Portions of the 1977 film ''[[Slap Shot]]'' starring [[Paul Newman]] were filmed at the Utica Memorial Auditorium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uticaod.com/sports/hockey/x1015940764/Hanson-Brothers-will-return-to-Utica-Aud |title='Hanson Brothers' will return to Utica Aud |author=Fran Perritano |date=May 28, 2010 |work=Utica Observer-Dispatch |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> *The American television program ''[[The Simpsons]]'' makes occasional reference to Utica. ** [[Superintendent Chalmers]] is from Utica.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snpp.com/episodes/3F18.html |title=22 Short Films About Springfield |work=The Simpsons Archive |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> ** The [[Eeny Teeny Maya Moe]] episode (#LABF06) shows a hockey game between the Springfield Isotopes and the [[Clinton Comets#Other Hockey Teams in the Mohawk Valley|Utica Mohawks]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} ** Another episode features an old newsreel that ends with the narrator exclaiming, "So watch out, Utica! Springfield is a city on the... grow!"{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} * The American television program ''[[The Office (US TV series)|The Office]]'' makes occasional reference to Utica: The "Utica branch" is one of a handful of the fictional company [[Dunder-Mifflin]]'s satellite offices, and has been mentioned sporadically throughout the show. **The [[Branch Wars]] episode is set partly in Utica. It was not filmed there, so the Mohawk Valley Chamber of Commerce and other local groups donated objects to [[Set dressing|dress]] the set to look like an actual Utica-style office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uticaod.com/lifestyles/x680961757 |title='The Office' in a Utica state of mind |author=Elizabeth Cooper |date=October 3, 2007 |work=Utica Observer-Dispatch |publisher= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wktv.com/news/local/10949656.html |title=A peek at the Utica Branch of NBC's "The Office" |author=Dave Dellecese |date=November 1, 2007 |work=WKTV Utica |publisher= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> **The [[Lecture Circuit|Lecture Circuit Pt. 1]] episode is also partly set in Utica.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title=The Office, "Lecture Circuit, Part One": The closure |work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |date=February 6, 2009 |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2009/02/the_office_lecture_circuit_par.html |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvovermind.com/nbc/the-office/the-office-lecture-circuit-pt-1-recap/1279 |title=The Office: ‘Lecture Circuit – Pt. 1′ Recap |author=CastawayCayley |date=February 10, 2009 |work=TV Overmind |publisher= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> *Bobbi Anderson, the protagonist of Stephen King's novel ''[[The Tommyknockers]]'', is from Utica.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hodder.co.uk/Assets/WorkAssets/Extracts/The%20Tommyknockers.pdf |title=The Tommyknockers (extract) |author=Stephen King |date= |work= |publisher= |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> * On ''[[The Honeymooners]]'' 1950s television show starring Jackie Gleason, Alice's Uncle is from Utica. * The protagonist of the 1997-1998 NBC sitcom ''[[Jenny (TV series)|Jenny]]'', starring [[Jenny McCarthy]], is from Utica and the series begins there. *The character Dr. Albert Hirsch from the Bourne film series is from Utica, NY as noted in documents reviewed by the character Pamela "Pam" Landy during the 2007 film The [[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|Bourne Utimatium]].<ref>[http://filmpilgrim.blogspot.com/2007/09/bourne-ultimatum.html The Film Pilgrim: The Bourne Ultimatum<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
